Application on Trees (Binary Search Tree for Student Records)
1. Scenario

In a college system, student records need to be stored and accessed efficiently. Each student has a unique ID. Operations like inserting new students, searching for a student, and displaying student IDs in sorted order are frequently required.

A Binary Search Tree (BST) is used to manage these student IDs efficiently:

Smaller IDs go to the left subtree
Larger IDs go to the right subtree
This structure allows quick searching and sorted traversal.
2. Justification

Using a BST is appropriate because:

It provides efficient search, insertion, and deletion operations.
It maintains sorted order automatically using inorder traversal.
Compared to linear structures (like arrays or linked lists), BST significantly reduces search time.

Why BST over other structures?

Arrays → slow insertion/deletion (O(n))
Linked Lists → slow searching (O(n))
BST → average-case efficient operations (O(log n))
3. Algorithm and Time Complexity
Insertion Algorithm
If root is NULL → create a new node.
If ID < root → insert in left subtree.
If ID > root → insert in right subtree.
Return root.

Time Complexity:

Best/Average Case: O(log n)
Worst Case (skewed tree): O(n)
Search Algorithm
If root is NULL or ID matches → return node.
If ID < root → search left subtree.
Else → search right subtree.

Time Complexity:

Best/Average Case: O(log n)
Worst Case: O(n)
Inorder Traversal Algorithm
Traverse left subtree
Visit root
Traverse right subtree

Time Complexity:

Always: O(n)
4. Code (C Program)
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Structure for BST Node
struct Node {
    int id;
    struct Node *left, *right;
};

// Create new node
struct Node* createNode(int id) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->id = id;
    newNode->left = newNode->right = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

// Insert node into BST
struct Node* insert(struct Node* root, int id) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return createNode(id);

    if (id < root->id)
        root->left = insert(root->left, id);
    else if (id > root->id)
        root->right = insert(root->right, id);

    return root;
}

// Search in BST
struct Node* search(struct Node* root, int id) {
    if (root == NULL || root->id == id)
        return root;

    if (id < root->id)
        return search(root->left, id);

    return search(root->right, id);
}

// Inorder traversal
void inorder(struct Node* root) {
    if (root != NULL) {
        inorder(root->left);
        printf("%d ", root->id);
        inorder(root->right);
    }
}

// Main function
int main() {
    struct Node* root = NULL;

    // Insert sample student IDs
    root = insert(root, 50);
    insert(root, 30);
    insert(root, 20);
    insert(root, 40);
    insert(root, 70);
    insert(root, 60);
    insert(root, 80);

    printf("Inorder Traversal (Sorted Student IDs): ");
    inorder(root);

    int key = 40;
    if (search(root, key))
        printf("\nStudent with ID %d found.\n", key);
    else
        printf("\nStudent with ID %d not found.\n", key);

    return 0;
}
